Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the jagged edge of midnight’s silent blade;
let shadows coil around your wandering wrist,
through moonlit groves where silent phantoms played.
Steal breath from roses trembling in the dew,
pluck stars like beads from heaven’s loosened seam;
let every hush be broken just by you,
a wildfire born of a sunlit dream.
Run where the ocean gnaws the crumbling shore,
dare tides to catch the echo of your name;
leave footprints that the winds will whisper for,
brief as sparks, yet bright beyond a flame.
For time will tame the fire in your eyes,
and sorrow weave its thread through golden hair;
so be the storm before the calm arrives,
be lightning clothed in jasmine-scented air.
Go, go, my girl—defy the quiet earth,
and kiss the sky to prove you had such worth.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the edge of dreams where reason starts to fray;
let logic drown beneath your siren hiss,
and dance where moonlight bleeds into the day.
You were not made for fences, rules, or clocks,
nor for the hush of well-behaved despair;
you bloom in cracks, atop forbidden rocks,
and scatter stardust in the common air.
Kiss the wild beast with eyes of molten gold,
the one that snarls but knows your name by heart;
let courage be the story you unfold,
even when the map falls apart.
For time will dim the fire in your veins,
and duty call you toward a quieter shore;
but now—the world is yours to break and frame,
to love, to leave, to kiss, to roar.
So take the sky, unravel its deep blue,
and kiss the stars until they whisper, "You."

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the ghost that haunts the attic of my chest;
let silence crack beneath your fingertips,
and wake the songs that slumbered with the rest.
You are the spark that lights the wick of time,
the giggle in the hush of ancient halls;
you steal the breath from verses left in rhyme,
and leap across the cracks where darkness falls.
Kiss the painter blind to his own art,
the singer choked by silence in his throat;
let every touch unravel guarded hearts,
and turn their pain to something they can note.
For one day you will tire, your voice grow thin,
and memories will flutter like old leaves;
but now—you dance where few have dared to begin,
and spin the world on fingertips and eves.
Go, go—with thunder in your blood and hair,
and kiss the sky like you were born to dare.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the outlaw hiding in the forest deep;
let his scars dissolve beneath your bliss,
and sing him lullabies while shadows sleep.
You are the flame that licks the frozen stream,
the whisper that unbinds a prisoner’s hands;
you live inside a half-remembered dream,
where truth and fantasy are both demands.
Kiss the poet who has lost his rhyme,
the widow clutching memories like stones;
let every touch rewrite the lines of time,
and build new worlds from fractured, aching bones.
Not for the timid was the night designed,
nor for the ones who fear the unknown call;
you leap where others pause, both heart and mind,
and rise each time, no matter how you fall.
So go—your footsteps shake the fabric of the air,
and kiss the storm like you were born to dare.

